name: 3,5-diphenyl-1h-pyrazole

The basic unit for our comparison will be benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of two additional phenyl rings. Phenyl groups, when connected to a benzene ring, tend to increase the melting point due to the enhancement of the crystalline structure and the increase in molecular weight. In the case of 3,5-diphenyl-1H-pyrazole, we have two additional phenyl rings linked in a linear fashion, which would notably augment the melting point.
